##Global shortage of masks, how to buy masks overseas?

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

World Health Organization (WHO) director-general Tan Desai said that the demand for face masks, protective clothing, gloves and other medical devices has recently increased 100-fold, prices have also increased 20-fold, the backlog of orders reached 4-6 months, have a very serious impact on the global production supply chain

By Wang Xiaofeng, CAIJING correspondent

Editor | Hao Zhou

"Send them all to me. " Wang told an Indian customer on Wechat that the customer had just found a batch of two-layer masks for him, and Wang immediately told him to place all orders.

Wang Zhongliang is the foreign trade director of Nanjing Yigao Microwave System Engineering Co. , Ltd. , which is a medical equipment manufacturer. After the outbreak of the COVID-19, his day job was to source masks around the world. Over the past two weeks, his team has purchased 110,000 surgical masks, 20,000 N95 masks, and 2,000 protective suits, the supplies have all been donated to six hospitals in Wuhan, three in Shandong Province and one in Harbin.

As supplies have dwindled, surgical masks have become more expensive, rising from 0.4 yuan to just 3 yuan, and N95 masks as high as 20 yuan. "The first batch of goods ordered from India was 0.5 yuan per unit, and the second batch went straight up to 2.5 yuan per unit, " Wang told Caijing. "I'm still shopping today, and now I need 3 yuan per unit. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wang Zhongliang team and customers in India to ask about the supply of masks

The outbreak of the new crown has put an extra strain on the global supply of face masks and other medical protective equipment, said Tan Desai, director-general of the World Health Organization (WHO) , demand for face masks, protective clothing, gloves and other medical devices has recently increased 100-fold, prices have also increased 20-fold, the accumulation of orders to 4-6 months, the global production supply chain has had a very serious impact.

The global production capacity of face masks is 40 million a day, half of them in China. With work not yet fully resumed in China and uncertainty over the development of the epidemic, the need for face masks has surged in China, leaving many Chinese companies and individuals to stock up on face masks in the global market. They also buy masks for different purposes, from personal use, to bulk purchases commissioned by companies for distribution to employees after work resumes, to donations to medical institutions.

Difficult docking of resources

The cost of buying masks is not astronomical, and it is difficult for buyers to source them even when they are desperately out of stock. At present, the main ways to find overseas supply are to buy back Chinese masks for export, to find overseas enterprises to order production and to integrate the scattered resources through local dealers to make up the odd number.

This kind of difficulty is beyond Wang Zhongliang's imagination. Their purchasing team was set up on the 30th day of the Lunar New Year because they anticipated that medical institutions would face a shortage of medical care appliances, they initially selected 10 approved masks from a list of customers around the world, but were slow to place orders and found that half of them were sold out before other buyers could get to them, that leaves India, Egypt, Tunisia and Thailand.

"We didn't fully realize at the time that this [ outbreak ] was so urgent that the goods were gone, " Wang said with a sigh

Fortunately, the Turkish customer is very strong, this person in charge of mask orders, the first time rushed to the mask factory to pull back 30,000 surgical masks, put them in the office, and at the same time to the local mask factory placed 100,000 orders, and after personally go to the mask factory squatting, because the order is too much, only in this way to ensure first come first get goods.

"All of these masks are sent to China by express mail, because it's by air and the cost of shipping is higher than the value of the masks themselves. At that time, the price of masks was not expensive, 0.4 yuan per face mask, and 30,000 face masks totaled about 12,000 yuan, but the freight cost was 15,000 yuan,"Wang said.

It also takes a week to get the goods from Turkey to a Chinese hospital, a process that can not go wrong in Split Second.

International Express will choose civil flights to carry cargo. The epidemic has led to a reduction in civil flights, which will delay the transport of masks. Wang Zhongliang's team should keep a close eye on the cargo flow, call the express company on every transfer to make sure the mask gets on the first flight out. After arriving in China, the logistics company is now understaffed, to communicate in advance with the airport, inform the material is donated medical supplies, speed up customs clearance, and transfer to the next process.

The 30,000 masks, the first to be purchased by Wang's team, have been shipped home and distributed to the Wuhan Union Hospital, affiliated to the Tongji Medical College, a small number went to Shandong.

In order to ensure the timely distribution of masks, they use direct donations from hospitals, purchase and deliver the products according to the specific needs of hospitals, and use the offices in Hubei to meet the needs of Wuhan Hospital, and even to refine the needs of each department. The logistics company sent the masks to Yigao's office in Wuhan, where they were then sent to the hospital in person.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Epidemic Relief Materials donated by Nanjing Yigao Medical Equipment Co. , Ltd. .

Racing against a face mask export restriction order

As the new crown epidemic spreads across the globe, demand for masks is soaring. In order to guarantee the supply, many countries take measures to restrict exports to guarantee the supply of masks. Thailand, for example, has announced that it will restrict exports of face masks to 500 at a time, otherwise they will be refused permission to leave the country. India also announced restrictions on exports of surgical masks after the first new case of coronavirus infection was confirmed in January. The ban on exports of surgical masks has been temporarily lifted, but the restrictions on exports of N95 masks remain in place. Russia, Iran and other countries issued an early warning that if the mask demand continued to rise, may follow the restrictions on masks out of the country.

Although some countries have not banned the export of face masks completely, they have limited the export of face masks to some extent, considering that their medical resources are not developed. For example, Egypt used to rely heavily on imports from China, but after the outbreak of the new coronavirus, the supply and demand relationship reversed and Egypt received large orders from China, but considering that the orders exceeded its production capacity and the local supply of masks was insufficient, together with new cases of suspected pneumonia in Egypt was confirmed, the Egyptian side canceled orders and restrictions on exports of face masks.

The ban on face masks poses difficulties in the procurement of face masks. "Egyptian clients have applied to the Ministry of Health several times for a ban on the export of masks from Egypt, but it has not yet been approved. In order to ship the masks out, Egyptian customers had to adopt a curved policy, first bringing the masks to Greece manually by passengers, and then transporting them back to China via Greece,"Wang said.

After India issued a ban on the export of surgical masks, Wang's Indian clients divided 20,000 surgical masks into 15 small packages, each the size of a small suitcase, and mailed them to 15 different places in China. Dismantling into small packages not only increase freight costs, but also increase the time cost of customs clearance, divided into 15 packages, equivalent to customs clearance 15 times, delay mask turnover time. To ensure a smooth customs clearance, they also changed the name of the product to medical accessories, rather than the written mask.

"there are some irregularities, but this is the only way to deal with such an emergency, " Wang said.

N95 masks are more difficult to procure than surgical masks because of low availability and tight control. Not every country has the capacity to produce N95 masks. The main N95 production capacity is in China. Wang Zhongliang can only be purchased in Turkey and India, and the masks in Turkey are exported by mistake and then sold domestically. This batch of masks is made in Suzhou. Turkish customers ordered them last year, so there are some stocks, learned that China needs, the original price was sold to billion Gao.

In addition to medical professional enterprises using industry trade resources to purchase donated masks, some overseas Chinese also use their own resources to purchase a large number of masks overseas. Zhang Yuanxiang, president of the General Chamber of Commerce and Village Association of Hebei, Kenya, has donated 300,000 surgical masks to the country since the outbreak.

Instead of looking for a local distributor to work with, he chose to place orders directly with the factory. On Jan. 25, when the Hebei Chamber of Commerce in Kenya launched a donation drive, Zhang found a local factory that produces surgical masks and placed an order for 300,000 masks before they became a global shopping spree, the price is about 0.5 yuan per head.

Such a large number of masks out of customs, they have to solve the channel out of customs. Unlike trade exports, which require special procedures for such charitable donations, Zhang contacted officials at the Chinese Embassy in Kenya and, through them, the Red Cross in his country, the Red Cross identified their receiving units as Wuhan Union Hospital and a hospital in Huanggang. China Southern Airlines also received approval to ship the donated masks to China for free.

The 300,000 masks are scheduled to leave for China on January 29. However, Zhang's orders have been hit by a run on resources because so many Chinese are buying masks. A Chinese company, which has a factory in Guangzhou, cut off Zhang's face masks for a high cash price in response to a resumption of work. Cut Hu let Zhang Yuanxiang very unprepared, he negotiated with the other side, hoping to sell some, can buy at a high price, the other side did not agree. Zhang could only buy more than 110,000 masks from other enterprises at a high price and put them on the plane at the last minute.

"Mask prices have gone up overseas, so it has become a war to get masks, " Zhang told CAIJING. Amid the buying frenzy, he realized that the Kenyan government might have to restrict exports of face masks because the country's health care resources are underdeveloped and must act quickly to ship a second batch of masks on the Feb. 7 flight.

In order for the factory to step up production of 200,000 masks, Zhang Yuanxiang not only paid a high price but also promised to help the factory managers solve the problem of children's employment. Finally, they made the other side to produce full speed, because the machine was running at high speed, and even broke down for a time, fortunately, the repairs allowed production to continue and were finally completed on February 6.

As the supply of face masks has escalated, cargo resources have become increasingly scarce as the few flights still operating, combined with a surge in the volume of supplies being delivered, have added to the pressure of insufficient capacity. Zhang Yuanxiang with 200,000 masks came to the airport, to see all the institutions of the materials piled up in the airport, freight warehouse has been full. In order to allow the cargo to be shipped back to China, China Southern made an exception to the mask on the seat shipped back to China. Shortly after the second batch of masks left Kenya, the Kenyan Ministry of Customs and health issued an order restricting the export of masks.

A face mask for arriving in the country on a "sitting" plane

Overseas charities are on the move

In addition to ordering supplies, overseas Chinese have mobilized local charities to donate masks to China, as many charities and international organizations have resources for medical devices. Pittsburgh, PA. , a sister city of Wuhan, donated 180,000 surgical masks to non-governmental organization this week.

Bbf, a charity based on in-kind donations, has long been committed to the global eradication of infectious diseases such as smallpox and polio since its founding in 1958, more than 105,000 tons of medicines, medical equipment, textbooks, educational supplies and emergency relief assistance have been provided to 149 countries.

"We started this donation campaign because we saw the new pneumonia ravaging China and it struck a chord with us. It just so happens that the Pittsburgh sister city agency staff also came to us, hoping that the BBF could help Wuhan,"BBF Disaster Assistance Director Sarah Bor told Caijing.

The BBF began to mobilize various social contacts to send the masks to China. They contacted local Chinese organizations, including the Pittsburgh Branch of the China Association for Travel and Science and technology in the United States (CAST-P) , which were supportive of the BBF idea, and offer whatever help you can. The Chinese community helped BBF contact the Chinese Consulate General in New York, handle customs clearance and other paperwork, contact the airline to transport the masks to China, and identify the Hubei Charity Federation as the Chinese counterpart.

"We couldn't have done it without the help of the Chinese community, " Sarah said.

Although there are no restrictions on exports of face masks in the United States, local supply of face masks became tight in the early stages of the outbreak and some supermarkets ran out of them. "There's a global shortage of masks, but the BBF happens to have a large stock of masks in its warehouse, and because we send a lot of medical supplies around the world to support people in need, we're getting donations all the time, and we just got a big donation of masks a while ago, " Sarah said.

The BBF has earmarked the masks to be donated to several Wuhan hospitals, including the Wuhan University of Science and Technology, which has long been linked to the school and has decided to distribute them where they are most needed. The BBF is ready to receive information on the progress of the donation. They have received confirmation from the Hubei Charity Federation that the 180,000 surgical masks just donated have arrived at the Shanghai airport and passed through the Green Channel, the logistics to the Wuhan Hospital are Alibaba and another company, and BBF is informed of every joint and every joint.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Donations from the BBF

"We want to donate more, but we haven't given supplies to China in a long time, and we want to make sure that the donations are well received and that the people who need them can get masks, so this 180,000 is just a trial run, and we will donate more masks in the future, " Sarah said.

The BBF website is currently up and running with a donation for new pneumonia in China, and while it's not much, BBF chairman Samad is confident it will grow. The donations will be used to buy masks and pay for shipping, and they are looking for N95 masks for hospitals in Wuhan, despite a severe shortage of supplies. Chinese President Xi Jinping said in a phone call with U.S. President Donald Trump on Feb. 7 that China and the United States have been in communication on the prevention and control of the epidemic, and thanked various sectors of the U.S. society for their material donations.
